**Description:** After Sabatier/MOXIE-derived LOX and LCH4 production, the propellants must be liquefied (90 K for LOX, 111 K for LCH4) and stored for 300–500 sols with zero boil-off using active cryocoolers (e.g., 150 W @ 90 K pulse-tube units). Martian dust (1.5 µm basaltic particles, electrostatically charged) settles on external radiators, increasing thermal resistance and degrading rejection efficiency under variable solar flux and 600 Pa CO₂ environment. No long-duration, dust-exposed flight-qualified radiator/cryocooler system exists for multi-ton propellant depots.

